## Blue, Red und Purple Counties?

::::::: columns
:::: {.column width="70%"}
### Differenz im Wähleranteil zur Präsidentschaftswahl 2020

```{r fig.show="hold", fig.width=10, fig.height=5.625}
#| echo: false
#| warning: false
#| message: false

nyt2020 <- read_csv("01_Daten/nyt_counties_final12042020.csv") %>% 
  mutate(dem_percent = bidenj/total.votes * 100,
         rep_percent = trumpd/total.votes * 100,
         Differenz = round(rep_percent - dem_percent, 1))

us_counties <- counties(cb = TRUE, resolution = "20m", progress_bar = FALSE) %>%
  filter(STATE_NAME  != "Puerto Rico") %>%
  shift_geometry() %>% 
  rename("County" = "NAME",
         "Bundesstaat" = "STATE_NAME") %>% 
  sf::st_cast("MULTIPOLYGON")

us_counties_joined <- us_counties %>% 
  left_join(nyt2020, by = c("GEOID" = "fips")) %>% 
  sf::st_cast("MULTIPOLYGON")

election_2020_percdiff_county <-
  ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = us_counties_joined,
          mapping = aes(fill = Differenz,
                        color = Differenz,
                        text = paste("Bundesstaat:", Bundesstaat,
                                     "<br>County:", County,
                                     "<br>Differenz:", Differenz)))  +
  geom_sf(data = us_states_joined,
          fill = "transparent",
          color = "white",
          lwd = 0.2 ) +
  scale_color_gradient2("", low = "blue",
                        mid = scales::muted("purple"),
                        high = "red",
                        breaks =  c(-25, 0, 25, 50, 75)) +
  scale_fill_gradient2("", low = "blue",
                       mid = scales::muted("purple"),
                       high = "red",
                       breaks =  c(-25, 0, 25, 50, 75)) +
  theme_void() +
  theme(legend.key.height = unit(3, "cm"),
        legend.key.width = unit(0.25, "cm"),
        axis.line = element_blank())

election_2020_percdiff_county <-
  ggplotly(election_2020_percdiff_county,
           tooltip = "text")

election_2020_percdiff_county

```

::: {style="font-size: 0.7em;"}
**Quelle:** Eigene Darstellung. Datenquelle: New York Times.
:::
::::

:::: {.column width="30%"}
-   **Demokraten** erzielen Erfolge vor allem in **urbanen Zentren** (z. B. die "East Coast" und "West Coast")
-   **Republikaner** sind im **ländlichen Raum** erfolgreich (z. B. in den "Heartlands" oder im "Bible Belt")
-   **Ursache:** Unterschiedliche **Bevölkerungsgruppen** konzentrieren sich geografisch
::::
:::::::

